<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-201-222 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 438 541</DOCID><JOURNAL>San Jose Mercury News  March 13 1991 p1C(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Too much war, violence? Computer games questioned. (at theComputer Game Developers Conference)</TITLE><AUTHOR>O'Connor, Rory J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Attendees at the Computer Game Developers Conference discuss theethics of designing games based upon war, violence and sexism.andO;Designers agree that conflict is an essential aspect of games ifthey are to be entertaining, but they question whether violence isequally necessary.andP;  The Persian Gulf war has increased sales ofwar games, but many are concerned about the effects of marketingviolent games.andP;  Designers suspect that a bill may be proposed toregulate violence in games, but designers would rather see aself-policing body instated similar to those that rate movies.andO;Designers also confronted the issue of sexism in games.andP;  Mostgames are written by, for and about young white males.andP;  Productsgenerally lack ethnic diversity and representation of woman.andP;  Whenfemale characters are part of a game they mirror male behavior orserve as 'rewards' for male characters.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer GamesComputer Games Developers ConferenceConferences and MeetingsEthicsEntertainmentSoftware PackagesCreativity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>